<p>
	This is the most common way of defining a custom validator. The first argument matches all inputs you want to validate. Here we select input fields whose <samp>type</samp> attribute is equal to "time". The second argument is the error message that is shown when validation fails. The third argument is the actual validator function; it must return <samp>true</samp> if the value is valid. The value is supplied as the second argument to the validator function.
</p>

<h3><samp>data-equals</samp> attribute</h3>

<p>
	Our next validator ensures that one field's value is equal to another field's value. For example <samp>data-equals="password"</samp> means that the value must equal to a field named "password". The <samp>data-</samp> prefix makes it valid HTML5.
</p>

